│ %n.vec of type i32.\n- The debug-only log shows execution reaching            │
│ VPScalarIVStepsRecipe::execute and then failing at                            │
│ Builder.CreateTrunc(StartIdx0, IntStepTy).\n- On AIX target datalayout,       │
│ BaseIVTy is double (64-bit), hence IntStepTy becomes i64. StartIdx0 is        │
│ computed from getOperand(2) and may be i32 (e.g., derived from %n.vec or      │
│ similar). Truncating i32 to i64 is illegal (should be an extension),          │
│ triggering the assertion.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nIn                      │
│ VPScalarIVStepsRecipe::execute, StartIdx0 is set from                         │
│ State.get(getOperand(2), true). If getUnrollPart(*this) != 0, we may multiply │
│ it and then perform Builder.CreateTrunc(StartIdx0, IntStepTy). The code       │
│ assumes IntStepTy is narrower or equal to StartIdx0 type, but with            │
│ floating-point inductions using BaseIVTy=double (64-bit), IntStepTy is i64    │
│ while StartIdx0 can be i32 (coming from vector-trip-count or part index on    │
│ 32-bit targets). Using CreateTrunc to convert i32 -> i64 is invalid and       │
│ asserts. The correct operation should be a width adjustment that extends when │
│ the destination is wider and truncates when narrower, i.e., CreateZExtOrTrunc │
│ or CreateSExtOrTrunc depending on signedness. Since StartIdx0 represents an   │
│ index/unroll start and is non-negative, zero-extend is appropriate. LLVM      │
│ often uses CreateZExtOrTrunc for index-like values.\n\n4. Proposed Edit       │
│ Point(s):\n- File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp\n- Line:    │
│ 2130\n- Change: Replace `StartIdx0 = Builder.CreateTrunc(StartIdx0,           │
│ IntStepTy);` with `StartIdx0 = Builder.CreateZExtOrTrunc(StartIdx0,           │
│ IntStepTy);`\n\nRationale: This ensures the cast is valid regardless of       │
│ source/destination bit widths and matches the semantics for index values      │
│ (non-negative). It mirrors similar patterns used elsewhere in VPlan recipes   │
│ (e.g., VPVectorEndPointerRecipe uses CreateZExtOrTrunc for RunTimeVF to match │
