│ and then failing at Builder.CreateTrunc(StartIdx0, IntStepTy).                │
│ - On AIX target datalayout, BaseIVTy is double (64-bit), hence IntStepTy      │
│ becomes i64. StartIdx0 is computed from getOperand(2) and may be i32 (e.g.,   │
│ derived from %n.vec or similar). Truncating i32 to i64 is illegal (should be  │
│ an extension), triggering the assertion.                                      │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ In VPScalarIVStepsRecipe::execute, StartIdx0 is set from                      │
│ State.get(getOperand(2), true). If getUnrollPart(*this) != 0, we may multiply │
│ it and then perform Builder.CreateTrunc(StartIdx0, IntStepTy). The code       │
│ assumes IntStepTy is narrower or equal to StartIdx0 type, but with            │
│ floating-point inductions using BaseIVTy=double (64-bit), IntStepTy is i64    │
│ while StartIdx0 can be i32 (coming from vector-trip-count or part index on    │
│ 32-bit targets). Using CreateTrunc to convert i32 -> i64 is invalid and       │
│ asserts. The correct operation should be a width adjustment that extends when │
│ the destination is wider and truncates when narrower, i.e., CreateZExtOrTrunc │
│ or CreateSExtOrTrunc depending on signedness. Since StartIdx0 represents an   │
│ index/unroll start and is non-negative, zero-extend is appropriate. LLVM      │
│ often uses CreateZExtOrTrunc for index-like values.                           │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ - File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp                        │
│ - Line: 2130                                                                  │
│ - Change: Replace `StartIdx0 = Builder.CreateTrunc(StartIdx0, IntStepTy);`    │
│ with `StartIdx0 = Builder.CreateZExtOrTrunc(StartIdx0, IntStepTy);`           │
│                                                                               │
│ Rationale: This ensures the cast is valid regardless of source/destination    │
│ bit widths and matches the semantics for index values (non-negative). It      │
│ mirrors similar patterns used elsewhere in VPlan recipes (e.g.,               │
│ VPVectorEndPointerRecipe uses CreateZExtOrTrunc for RunTimeVF to match        │
│ IndexTy).                                                                     │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The assertion stems from an invalid truncation when widening i32 to i64 in    │
│ VPScalarIVStepsRecipe::execute on targets where BaseIVTy is 64-bit FP but     │
│ index types are 32-bit. Using CreateZExtOrTrunc fixes the type adjustment,    │
│ preventing the invalid constantexpr cast and allowing the loop-vectorizer to  │
│ proceed. This change is safe, consistent with index semantics, and aligns     │
│ with existing code patterns in vector pointer/end pointer recipes.            │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
